An exploration of IMDB data using machine learning techniques¶

Introduction¶

The film industry receives substantial annual box office revenue which is a motivation for analysing the factors influencing the financial success of films. In 2012 revenues exceeded \$10.8 Billion (US/Canada) but despite this there are unsuccessful movies released almost every year (Lash and Zhao, 2016). By identifying the variables that contribute toward profitability it can reduce the risk of production companies releasing a flop. In this report IMDB data was used to perform machine learning techniques in order to address this issue.

This report establishes what is known in literature about modelling the success of movies. The data is explored via univariate and bivariate analysis. Clustering is performed to understand patterns in movie preferences. Regression analysis is performed to predict revenue. The models are then evaluated with discussions on their implications.

Literature review¶

Previous studies have investigated the variables determining the success of a film, they can be used to guide the selection of variables for clustering and predictors in regression analysis. The literature suggests a films success is influenced by star power, genre, director and viewer ratings. Meenakshi et al. (2018) used k-means clustering to gauge a films success via generating clusters of 3 categories; Flop, Average, Hit. The study used popular actors, genres and composers to produce clusters. Krushikanth et al. (2013) used k-means clustering to show how online rating and sentiment, on platforms such as YouTube, predict a films success. Song and Hana (2013) found determinants of financial success may include star actors, release date, rating and whether it is a sequel. Lash and Zhao (2016) highlight the importance of star power where individual actors have a name brand effect improving financial performance.

The dataset¶

This study used IMDB datasets containing summary and rating data related to 85,855 films. In order to enable greater specificity not every film was considered. The dataset was filtered to ensure films were a USA release, feature length, the profits and budgets were USD, release date was after 1990, it had over 100 votes. These filters reduced the dataset to 5,829 films. These filters were set to guarantee films were established full length theatrical releases and mitigate issues regarding currency exchange rates and financial inflation. This dataset was supplemented by a list containing the top 100 most lucrative film stars. It is key to highlight that one film can have multiple genres. The core genres and production_companies were derived from those most abundant.

#The rest were recoded as other.
#genreate a list of core genres
core_genres = ['Drama', 'Action', 'Comedy', 'Animation','Romance','Family','Horror', 'Crime']
#function to class other non-core categories
def my_recode4(genre):
    for genre in genre:
        if genre in core_genres:
            return 0
        else:
            return 1        
#building dummy variables for genres by frist splitting the string list
test = dbj1_world_dollars.genre.str.join('|').str.get_dummies()
test =  test.groupby(by=test.columns, axis=1).sum()
#create an other_genre class for the non core genres
dbj1_world_dollars['other_genre'] =  dbj1_world_dollars['genre'].apply(my_recode4)
dbj1_world_dollars = dbj1_world_dollars.join(test)
#building dummy variables for production comp
test2 = pd.get_dummies(dbj1_world_dollars[['production_company_R']] )
test2 =  test2.groupby(by=test2.columns, axis=1).sum()
dbj1_world_dollars = dbj1_world_dollars.join(test2)
#drop remaining non-core genres
dbj1_world_dollars = dbj1_world_dollars.drop(['Biography','Western','War','Sport','Sci-Fi','Musical','Music','History'], axis=1)
#reset index
dbj1_world_dollars = dbj1_world_dollars.reset_index(drop=True)

Univariate Analysis¶

Figure 1 shows the distribution of a selection of key continuous and categorical variables within the dataset. The first bar-plot shows there is a large number of unique production_companies because the mode is the other category (4000+), all other categories have counts less than 300. The second bar-plot for genre shows a greater distribution across the categories. The mode is Drama with a count of 3,000+ therefore genre is skewed towards this class. All categories have a 300+ count. Considering the literature, genre appears to be a better candidate as a predictor variable in regression than production_company. The histograms in Figure 1 show the distribution of the mean_vote which has a gaussian distribution centred around 6.1. Similar distributions were identified in other rating-based variables such as: 'females_allages_avg_vote', 'males_allages_avg_vote', 'top1000_voters_rating', 'allgenders_45age_avg_vote', 'allgenders_18age_avg_vote', 'non_us_voters_rating'. The histogram for votes shows positively skewed data; a distribution also identified in the worldwide_gross_income (top-right). The distribution of the data was made more normally distributed using log transformations (bottom-right). Log transformation was also applied to votes and budget.

Bivariate Analysis¶

ESDA in Figure 2 helps to reveal whether there are any notable patterns between variables. The boxplots explore differences in the preferences of IMDB users regarding genre. This is important as this information can help production companies to select genres aimed at audience demographics. The boxplots show on average the younger audiences (allgenders_18age_avg_vote) gave more generous ratings with a mean higher than allgenders_aged45_avg_vote. Animation and Family films were rated more highly by the younger voter. Animation has the biggest difference between the average maximum rating given between ages. The second boxplot set shows that on average females consistently give more generous film ratings (females_all_ages_avg_vote). Animation and Family films display the greatest difference in mean vote and maximum rating between genders. Ignoring the demographic differences within both plots it is possible to identify the highest rated genre is Animation (averaging around 6.5) and the lowest rated is Horror (averaging around 5.7). The strip-plot illustrates the profit margins of films with reference to their production_company. It is clear from the plot that DreamWorks and MGM have more sporadic successes than Twentieth Century Fox and Warner Brothers, which have a higher frequency of films at different profit levels. The shaded KDE (bottom-right) identifies the hotspot for worldwide_gross_income is where the budget is around \$10 million and the worldwide_gross_income is \\$25 million. The KDE leans to the right showing that often the greater budget leads to greater revenue (but not always).

#Process for k-means clustering for imdb data
#reset index
dbj1_world_dollars = dbj1_world_dollars.reset_index(drop=True)

#set k-means with 4 clusters
estimator = KMeans(n_clusters = 4)
#fit the k-means model using the raw data
estimator.fit(dbj1_world_dollars[movie_categories])
#set labels 
k5_raw = pd.Series(estimator.labels_,
                       index=dbj1_world_dollars.index
                      )

#birch clustering using the raw data
estimator2 = Birch(threshold=0.01, n_clusters=4)
#fit the model suing the raw data
estimator2.fit(dbj1_world_dollars[movie_categories])
#set labels 
Birch5_raw = pd.Series(estimator2.labels_,
                       index=dbj1_world_dollars.index
                      )

#All standardised
# Minus mean, divided by std
db_stded = scale(dbj1_world_dollars[movie_categories])
#standardised - k-means
estimator = KMeans(n_clusters = 4)
#fit model using standardised data
estimator.fit(db_stded)
#set labels
k5_std = pd.Series(estimator.labels_,
                       index=dbj1_world_dollars.index
                      )

# Range scaled data fit to k-means
#use minmaxscaler to range scale data
range_scaler = MinMaxScaler()
#transform data to be scaled
db_scaled = range_scaler.fit_transform(dbj1_world_dollars[movie_categories])
#create k-means model for 4 clusters
estimator = KMeans(n_clusters = 4)
#fit the model using scaled data
estimator.fit(db_scaled)
#set labels
k5_scaled = pd.Series(estimator.labels_,
                       index=dbj1_world_dollars.index
                      )

#set up principle component analysis consisting of 2 components from the raw data
pca_estimator = PCA(n_components=2)
#fit PCA using imdb data
components = pca_estimator.fit_transform(dbj1_world_dollars[movie_categories])
#building the 2 PCA components as dataframe
components = pd.DataFrame(components,
                              index = dbj1_world_dollars.index,
                              columns = ["C-1", "C-2"]
                             )

#Now we cluster the two components instead of all the input variables:
#PCA k-means with 4 clusters
estimator = KMeans(n_clusters = 4)
#fit the model
estimator.fit(components)
#set labels
k5_pca = pd.Series(estimator.labels_,
                       index=components.index
                      )

    chs = calinski_harabasz_score(dbj1_world_dollars[movie_categories],

#Process for Silhoutte plot
#set components variable to be an array for Silhouette plot

X = components_array

#select 4 clusters for silhoutte plot

#assign axis labels for silhoutte plot
ax1 = axs[3,0]
ax2 = axs[3,1]

#use for loop to cycle through the clusters (in this case just the one for the 4 clusters)
for n_clusters in range_n_clusters:
    # Create a subplot with 1 row and 2 columns
    #fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2)
    #fig.set_size_inches(18, 7)

    # The 1st subplot is the silhouette plot
    # The silhouette coefficient can range from -1, 1 but in this example all
    # lie within [-0.1, 1]
    ax1.set_xlim([-0.1, 1])
    # The (n_clusters+1)*10 is for inserting blank space between silhouette
    # plots of individual clusters, to demarcate them clearly.
    ax1.set_ylim([0, len(X) + (n_clusters + 1) * 10])

    # Initialize the clusterer with n_clusters value and a random generator
    # seed of 10 for reproducibility.
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=10)
    cluster_labels = clusterer.fit_predict(X)

    # The silhouette_score gives the average value for all the samples.
    # This gives a perspective into the density and separation of the formed
    # clusters
    silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(X, cluster_labels)

    # Compute the silhouette scores for each sample
    sample_silhouette_values = silhouette_samples(X, cluster_labels)

    y_lower = 10
    for i in range(n_clusters):
        # Aggregate the silhouette scores for samples belonging to
        # cluster i, and sort them
        ith_cluster_silhouette_values = \
            sample_silhouette_values[cluster_labels == i]

        ith_cluster_silhouette_values.sort()

        size_cluster_i = ith_cluster_silhouette_values.shape[0]
        y_upper = y_lower + size_cluster_i

        color = cm.nipy_spectral(float(i) / n_clusters)
        ax1.fill_betweenx(np.arange(y_lower, y_upper),
                          0, ith_cluster_silhouette_values,
                          facecolor=color, edgecolor=color, alpha=0.7)

        # Label the silhouette plots with their cluster numbers at the middle
        ax1.text(-0.05, y_lower + 0.5 * size_cluster_i, str(i))

        # Compute the new y_lower for next plot
        y_lower = y_upper + 10  # 10 for the 0 samples

    ax1.set_title("The silhouette plot for the various clusters.")
    ax1.set_xlabel("The silhouette coefficient values")
    ax1.set_ylabel("Cluster label")

    # The vertical line for average silhouette score of all the values
    ax1.axvline(x=silhouette_avg, color="red", linestyle="--")

    ax1.set_yticks([])  # Clear the yaxis labels / ticks
    ax1.set_xticks([-0.1, 0, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1])

    # 2nd Plot showing the actual clusters formed
    colors = cm.nipy_spectral(cluster_labels.astype(float) / n_clusters)
    ax2.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], marker='.', s=30, lw=0, alpha=0.7,
                c=colors, edgecolor='k')

    # Labeling the clusters
    centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    # Draw white circles at cluster centers
    ax2.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], marker='o',
                c="white", alpha=1, s=200, edgecolor='k')

    for i, c in enumerate(centers):
        ax2.scatter(c[0], c[1], marker='$%d$' % i, alpha=1,
                    s=50, edgecolor='k')

    ax2.set_title("The visualization of the clustered raw data with labels.")
    ax2.set_xlabel("C-1")
    ax2.set_ylabel("C-2")
    
    #add a title, select fontsize 14 and bold
    plt.suptitle(("Figure 3 - KMeans clustering on film data "
                  "with n_clusters = %d" % n_clusters),
                 fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')

K-means Clustering¶

The unsupervised learning method chosen for this report was K-means clustering. It is used to classify the films into natural groupings where the Euclidean distance formula is used to make the clusters from data provided to the algorithm (Meenakshi et al., 2018). The variables chosen for clustering were those pertaining to film ratings and budget ('females_allages_avg_vote','males_allages_avg_vote', 'top1000_voters_rating', 'l_budget').

As K-means uses distance measures between examples it is good practice to standardise or scale data prior to clustering. In this study a model has been fitted for the scaled and raw data to illustrate the best outcome. Principal component analysis (PCA) was performed to summarise the chosen variables into 2 summary variables. This facilitates the creation of a scatter plot with these PCA variables on the x-axis and y-axis. K-means clusters for the PCA variables were also calculated. BIRCH clustering is a method primarily used for larger datasets it was also included as a comparison against k-means. In order to evaluate the quality of the clusters the data was plotted and Calinski and Harabasz (CH) scores were generated. This score increases as the clusters improve.

Cluster Evaluation¶

The graphics in Figure 3 shows there are minor visual differences in the 4 versions of clustering. The clusters of PCA and Raw are both similar in shape and CH score. The scaled data shows a notable difference in the locations of the cluster boundaries and a lower CH score. BIRCH clustering demonstrates fuzzy boundaries confirming that k-means is a stronger choice of algorithm in this context. The PCA, Raw and Scaled data have similar CH scores (3300+). The best of all these options is narrowly the Raw data which has the highest CH score of 3481.82.

The elbow method and silhouette plot can be used in order to establish the optimal number of clusters (k). The results of the elbow plot shows that a total of 4 clusters is best as the CH score is highest (3481). The silhouette plot demonstrates how close each point in one cluster is to the neighbouring ones. It identifies all 4 clusters have above average silhouette scores (beyond red line). It shows cluster_3 and cluster_0 contain the greatest number of films. It also identifies a minority of negative scores denoting that some potential incorrect cluster assignment.

The heatmap and Table 1 provide better insights into the clusters. It suggests they represent successful films and unsuccessful films (hits and flops). Clusters_0 and Cluster_3 and have similar average budgets (\$25 - 32 million) but Clusters_3 groups those that have been received better critically (6.6 average from top1000_voters_rating). Comparing Cluster_1 and Cluster_2 it shows groupings of lower budget films (\\$1 - 6 million) where the higher average budget has worse critical reception than Cluster_1. This information suggests further analysis of films in Cluster_2 may help to inform production companies on planning a hit movie without a large budget.

Supervised Learning¶

The outcome variable for the supervised learning analysis is l_worlwide_gross_income. Multivariate linear regression was used to generate prediction models.

Selection of predictor variables¶

Correlation tests were conducted to assist predictor variable selection. The results from these tests are documented in Appendix B. The results supported the findings in literature that rating (top1000_voters_rating), genre (Action), budget and the presence of a star_actor are good candidates. Using these variables, a baseline linear regression model and a subsequent augmented model was generated and compared (Table 2).

Model Summary¶

The baseline and augmented model have a statistically significance f-statistic (P<0.05), meaning the models provide a better fit than to a model without predictors (reject null hypothesis). The baseline model has a 0.604 R-squared value showing that 60.4% of the variance in l_worlwide_gross_income is explained by the predictors. Each predictor variable has a positive value the greatest of which is l_budget (1.227). The top1000_voters_rating is also important and can be interpreted as a 0.67 increase in rating leads to a 1 unit increase in l_worlwide_gross_income. The AIC (Akaikes Information Criteria) is a relative measure of model parsimony which accounts for the number of variables, the smaller this value the better fit. The baseline model has a value of 23905.8. The AIC of the augmented version of the model shows that despite the inclusion of an additional predictor (Action) the R-squared (60.4%) and AIC (23905) each did not improve, and the Action coefficient was unexpectedly a negative value. The baseline model is deemed the better in this instance.

Observed vs Predicted¶

Taking the set of fitted values generated from the baseline model (for the full dataset) it is possible to assess how good our model is at predicting l_worlwide_gross_income. Figure 4 shows how accurate it is using an observed example (Star Wars). It shows prediction has been relatively successful in this case (yellow and green lines similarly located). It also shows similar shaped distributions of observed and predicted but with greater error at the lower x-values. A point predictive simulation captures the uncertainty in the model running 2000 iterations taking a random draw of beta coefficients the result is the grey set of lines.

Figure 5 shows how the data points follow the model best fit line for the linear models (LM) using the raw data and transformed. As a contrast to the LM approach a Random forest (RF) model was generated on the same data. RF are an alternative algorithmic form of supervised learning, they are a collection of decision trees that use a ensemble approach to predict an outcome variable. A model generated via RFs can better account for the impact of outliers.

Table 3 shows the RF has a greater r-square value (0.89) and much lower Mean Square Error (MSE) (\$59,609,530) illustrating it is a powerful alternative method the LM. The MSE for the various model iterations is also shown in Table 3. Directly comparing the models to the baseline (LM-Raw) that has an MSE of $116,031,100, the error for the RF (RF-Raw) is over \$56 million less and the R-square is 89%.

Predictions with cross-validation¶

The previous models used all 5000+ films to train the model and generate predictions. It is important to understand the extent the model is applicable when applied to data it has not seen to mitigate overfitting. By splitting the data into a training set (60% split) and a test set (40%) it is possible to evaluate how good the model is at predicting unseen data. The results in Table 3 show that from this approach the MSE increases from \$116,031,100 to $161,169,020 (MSE_TT). In order to check the MSE values are not a symptom of the sample split allocation a further 5 k-fold cross-validations were run for the model. This MSE generated from this approach was slightly smaller at \$151,818023 (LM-CV).

Conclusion¶

The ESDA established the production_companies that have had less consistent revenue and which genres are popular with audiences. The unsupervised learning has provided insights into which hit movies were best value for money in terms of rating. The supervised learning has shown that with a limited number of predictor variables it is possible to estimate worlwide_gross_income with some degree of success particularly using RF. In order to improve the supervised models in future diagnostics such as checking multicollinearity can be performed and further variables as suggested by literature could be implemented.

#Appendix B - corellation coefficients

pearsoncorr1 = dbj1_world_dollars[['weighted_average_vote', 'allgenders_18age_avg_vote', 'allgenders_45age_avg_vote', 'l_worlwide_gross_income','year', 'l_budget','l_votes', 'avg_vote','top1000_voters_rating']].corr(method='pearson')
tableA = np.round(pearsoncorr1[['l_worlwide_gross_income']].sort_values(by = 'l_worlwide_gross_income', ascending=False), decimals=2)
tableA = tableA.reset_index()
tableA = tableA.rename(columns={"index":"Attribute","l_worlwide_gross_income":"Correlation Value" })
tableA = tableA[1:]

spearmancorr1 = dbj1_world_dollars[['Drama', 'Action', 'Comedy', 'Animation','Romance','Family','Horror', 'Crime', 'l_worlwide_gross_income', 'star_actor', 'oscar_winner_director']].corr(method='spearman')
tableB = np.round(spearmancorr1[['l_worlwide_gross_income']].sort_values(by = 'l_worlwide_gross_income', ascending=False), decimals=2)
tableB = tableB.reset_index()
tableB = tableB.rename(columns={"index":"Attribute","l_worlwide_gross_income":"Correlation Value" })
tableB = tableB[1:]

fig, axs =plt.subplots(2,1,figsize=(10, 8))
fig.patch.set_visible(False)

the_table = axs[0].table(cellText=tableA.values,colLabels=tableA.columns,loc='center', colColours = ["palegreen"] * 2)
axs[0].axis('off')
axs[0].set_title('Pearsons Correlation')

the_table = axs[1].table(cellText=tableB.values,colLabels=tableB.columns,loc='center', colColours = ["palegreen"] * 2)
axs[1].axis('off')
axs[1].set_title('Spearmans Correlation')
axs[1].axis('tight')
